",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite and mackinawite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"alkaline vent-like, anoxic, H2-rich\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Mineral-catalyzed reduction of CO2 by H2 on Fe-S surfaces to a reduced C1 product pool represented by formate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Included to satisfy the required hydrothermal-surface interconnection and provide a plausible reduced-carbon feed into later surface chemistry. This hydrothermal step follows the iron-sulfur vent framework specified in the system instructions, but the validated serine literature bundle explicitly notes that hydrothermal/iron-sulfur routes were searched and not promoted into the final retained serine route table, so this connection is speculative and only used as an environmental feeder, not as a literature-backed serine-specific route (Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997; Preiner et al., 2020; serine_s6_analysis.md).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_002\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal reduction of formate/CO2 pool to formaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_003\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_004\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe3O4)\", \"elemental iron (Fe0)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"400-500K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite and Fe0\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"anoxic subseafloor or vent-adjacent reducing conditions\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Further reduction of a C1 oxocarboxylate/carbon oxide pool to formaldehyde-like reduced carbon under Fischer-Tropsch-type hydrothermal catalysis.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Used as a hydrothermal source of formaldehyde to connect the required environments; this is not part of the validated final serine route table and therefore is marked as a necessary speculative feeder constrained by the system hydrothermal chemistry. The serine report emphasizes that hydrothermal angles were not retained as final serine routes (serine_s6_analysis.md), while reduced-carbon generation on magnetite/Fe surfaces is broadly supported in prebiotic catalysis literature (McCollom, 2013; Preiner et al., 2020; serine_s6_analysis.md).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_003\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface conversion of HCN hydrolysate pool to formamide\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_019\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_007\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO2 and phosphate minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"UV-exposed evaporative/formamide-rich surface setting\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"HCN in aqueous irradiated surface settings is converted through hydrolysis/photochemical processing into a formamide-bearing pool, represented here as direct access to formamide.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Formamide is a principal reagent/solvent in the strongest serine network routes. The validated report identifies formamide as central to SER-R1 to SER-R3 and also retains UV photochemistry from HCN-rich environments. The exact HCN-to-formamide preparative step is not itself route-ranked in the retained table, so this connector is necessary but partly inferred from the validated precursor network and broader HCN/formamide prebiotic chemistry (Green et al., 2023; Patel et al., 2015; serine_precursor_list.csv; serine_s6_analysis.md).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_004\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface formose-type production of glycolaldehyde from formaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_005\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"borate minerals and phosphate minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"evaporitic pool or hot-spring wet-dry concentration\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Surface concentration and carbonyl coupling generate C2 sugar precursors from formaldehyde, represented by glycolaldehyde formation.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Glycolaldehyde is the direct aldehydic precursor in the best-supported serine nitrile route (SER-R1). The validated report cites glycolaldehyde as a principal feedstock and links it to formose/cyanosulfidic chemistry, but does not give a single retained route row for formaldehyde-to-glycolaldehyde. This connector is therefore necessary to bridge the hydrothermal reduced-carbon supply to the literature-supported surface serine network (Green et al., 2023; Ritson & Sutherland, 2012; Ritson et al., 2013; serine_precursor_list.csv).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_005\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanosulfidic photoredox generation of glycolaldehyde, glyceraldehyde, glycolonitrile and serine aminonitrile pool\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_017\", \"mol_019\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_012\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)\", \"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"mild / non-hydrothermal\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"UV photoredox with sulfide mineral support\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"UV-exposed surface waters or post-impact ponds; hydrosulfide-driven cyanometal photoredox\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"HCN/cyanide and hydrosulfide under UV photoredox furnish sugar and aminonitrile precursor pools including glycolaldehyde, glyceraldehyde, glycolonitrile, and a serine-aminonitrile-containing output.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This reaction follows SER-R5 as a precursor-supply route. The validated report states that Patel et al. (2015) supports cyanosulfidic generation of glycolaldehyde/glyceraldehyde-class precursors and an alpha-aminonitrile pool including serine aminonitrile, though no serine-specific yield was retained. Because the system requires mineral agents for all surface reactions, sulfide minerals and TiO2 are specified as geochemically relevant supports, while the core chemistry remains the retained cyanosulfidic photoredox network (Patel et al., 2015; serine_reaction_table.csv; serine_s6_analysis.md).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_006\",\n      \"name\": \"HCN addition to glycolaldehyde to form glycolonitrile\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_006\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)\", \"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"mineral-assisted concentration in aqueous surface setting\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"cyanide-bearing pool, anoxic\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Cyanohydrin formation from glycolaldehyde and HCN gives glycolonitrile, a validated precursor linked to serine chemistry.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The validated precursor list explicitly identifies glycolonitrile as a cyanosulfidic precursor/feedstock linked to glycolaldehyde-class chemistry in serine networks. While no dedicated retained route row quantifies this isolated transformation for serine, it is directly supported as a precursor relation in the literature bundle and helps create the required convergent hub structure (Patel et al., 2015; Green et al., 2023; serine_precursor_list.csv).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_007\",\n      \"name\": \"Green formamide Strecker route from glycolaldehyde to serine nitrile\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_021\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\", \"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"RT 16 h; then 50 C 16 h; then 80 C 16 h\",\n        \"pressure\": \"ambient / open vessel\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"none additional in paper; mineral concentration support imposed by network constraints\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"formamide-rich solution; NaCN 3.0 equiv; NH4Cl 5.0 equiv; evaporative/warm drying microenvironment\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Strecker-like aminonitrile formation from glycolaldehyde in formamide-rich medium with cyanide and ammonium gives serine nitrile, with later progression toward N-formylserine nitrile upon continued heating.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is the core yield-backed route SER-R1. The validated report gives exact conditions and conversions: glycolaldehyde + NaCN + NH4Cl in formamide under RT to 50 C to 80 C sequence gave up to 36% serine nitrile and then 36% N-formylserine nitrile (Green et al., 2023, JACS, Table 3 row CH2OH; serine_route_yields.csv). Mineral agents are included only to satisfy the output schema constraint; the literature itself reports no added mineral catalyst for this step (Green et al., 2023; serine_s6_analysis.md).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_008\",\n      \"name\": \"Formamide-mediated N-formylation of serine nitrile to N-formylserine nitrile\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_007\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\", \"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"RT to 80 C\",\n        \"pressure\": \"ambient / open vessel\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"none additional in paper; mineral concentration support imposed by network constraints\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"false\",\n        \"other\": \"formamide solution; nitrate salt form of serine nitrile used in reported experiments\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Formamide acts as reagent/medium to N-formylate serine nitrile, producing a protected aminonitrile reservoir.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is SER-R2, the strongest quantitative step in the validated bundle. Green et al. (2023, JACS, Table 1 row 4a) reported conversion of serine nitrile to N-formylserine nitrile reaching 82% at +5 h 80 C. The validated report interprets this as protection/reservoir chemistry rather than direct free-serine synthesis (Green et al., 2023; serine_route_yields.csv; serine_s6_analysis.md). Mineral agents are network-required but not experimentally specified in the paper.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_009\",\n      \"name\": \"MgCl2-assisted warm formamide branching of serine nitrile\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_007\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_013\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_015\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\", \"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"50 C and 80 C\",\n        \"pressure\": \"ambient\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"MgCl2 5 equiv in formamide; mineral support imposed by network constraints\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"false\",\n        \"other\": \"drying/warming formamide chemistry; one condition used free-base Ser-CN prepared from pH 9.2 aqueous solution\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Under warm formamide conditions with MgCl2, serine nitrile partitions among N-formylserine nitrile and dehydrated/elaborated side branches including FoDHA-CN and Fo(beta-formylamino)alanine nitrile.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is SER-R3. The validated report provides exact product distributions from Green et al. (2023, JACS, Table 2 entry 3), including FoSer-CN, FoDHA-CN, and Fo(beta-formylamino)alanine nitrile under 50 C/80 C with MgCl2. This step is important because it shows both productive reservoir formation and attrition away from serine release (Green et al., 2023; serine_route_yields.csv; serine_s6_analysis.md).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_010\",\n      \"name\": \"Alkaline hydrolysis of N-formylaminonitrile pool to serine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_013\", \"mol_019\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_016\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [\"water\", \"base\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"not fully extracted\",\n        \"pressure\": \"not reported\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"alkaline aqueous processing\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"post-drying rehydration / aqueous processing; alkaline conditions\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Rehydration and alkaline hydrolysis of the protected aminonitrile reservoir release serine-related amino-acid products, represented here as serine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is SER-R4, the mechanistically crucial but quantitatively unresolved step. The validated report states that Green et al. (2023) describes alkaline processing of N-formylaminonitriles to mixtures of N-formylated and unformylated amino-acid derivatives, but a numeric free-serine yield was not found in checked text/SI. Therefore this terminal step is literature-retained but yield-unreported and should be treated as plausible rather than quantitatively established (Green et al., 2023; serine_route_yields.csv; serine_s6_analysis.md).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_011\",\n      \"name\": \"Alkaline hydrolysis of serine nitrile to serine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_019\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_016\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [\"water\", \"base\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"not fully extracted\",\n        \"pressure\": \"not reported\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"alkaline aqueous processing\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"post-formamide aqueous reprocessing; inferred parallel to N-formylaminonitrile hydrolysis\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Hydrolytic conversion of an aminonitrile to the corresponding amino acid under alkaline aqueous conditions.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is a necessary connector consistent with the validated interpretation that serine nitrile is the direct nitrile precursor to serine or serine-derived hydrolysates. The exact isolated serine-yield conditions were not quantified in the retained bundle, so this edge is inferred from the mechanistic role of serine nitrile in Green et al. (2023) and explicitly remains yield-unreported in this network (Green et al., 2023; serine_precursor_list.csv; serine_s6_analysis.md).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_012\",\n      \"name\": \"Ice-UV photochemistry and hydrolysis giving serine-containing residue\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_019\", \"mol_023\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_020\", \"mol_001\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_024\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"cryogenic irradiation followed by warm-up\",\n        \"pressure\": \"vacuum / low pressure during ice stage\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"UV/VUV irradiation; mineral collection support imposed by network constraints\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"false\",\n        \"other\": \"ice analog photochemistry followed by hydrolysis/workup\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"UV/VUV irradiation of mixed ices produces complex organics which, after warm-up and hydrolysis, yield amino-acid-containing residues including serine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This represents SER-R6. The validated report retains the astrochemical route family from Mu\u00f1oz Caro et al. (2002), Elsila et al. (2007), and Nuevo et al. (2008), with serine reported in hydrolyzed residues but without extracted quantitative yield in the validated bundle. The product is represented as a serine-containing residue pool to avoid overstating direct isolated serine production beyond the validated evidence (Mu\u00f1oz Caro et al., 2002; Elsila et al., 2007; Nuevo et al., 2008; serine_s6_analysis.md).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_013\",\n      \"name\": \"Recovery of serine from hydrolyzed ice-photochemistry residue\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_024\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_016\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [\"aqueous workup\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"warm-up / hydrolysis workup\",\n        \"pressure\": \"ambient after deposition stage\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"none\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"hydrolyzed residue analyzed for amino acids\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Amino-acid release and identification from complex photochemical residue, represented here as serine recovery.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This follows the retained interpretation of SER-R6 that serine is obtained after hydrolysis/workup of irradiated ice residues. Because the validated bundle does not give a numeric yield or a more detailed isolated preparative step, this is represented conservatively as serine recovery from the residue pool (Mu\u00f1oz Caro et al., 2002; Elsila et al., 2007; Nuevo et al., 2008; serine_reaction_table.csv).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_014\",\n      \"name\": \"Spark-discharge synthesis of amino acid mixture containing serine and glycine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_018\", \"mol_019\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_016\", \"mol_022\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"bulk apparatus mild; local spark/plasma hot\",\n        \"pressure\": \"not extracted\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"spark discharge; mineral collection support imposed by network constraints\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"reduced atmosphere simulation with condensed aqueous traps\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Electrical discharge through reduced gas mixtures forms amino-acid product mixtures in condensates, including serine and glycine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is SER-R7. The validated report states that Yu et al. (2014) found serine in discharge condensates, though no absolute serine yield was extracted. Glycine is also included because Miller-Urey-type mixtures commonly contain it and it is needed to connect the validated low-confidence hydroxymethylation route family retained in the serine bundle (Yu et al., 2014; serine_reaction_table.csv; serine_s6_analysis.md).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_015\",\n      \"name\": \"Formaldehyde plus glycine hydroxymethylation concept to serine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_022\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_016\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [\"none\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"not established from accessible primary text\",\n        \"pressure\": \"not reported\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"none securely established\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"formaldehyde-bearing surface waters or evaporative pools\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Conceptual beta-hydroxymethylation/carbon transfer from formaldehyde onto glycine to give serine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is SER-R8, retained as a low-confidence route. The validated report states that historical and source-list evidence supports the concept that formaldehyde supplies the beta-carbon of serine and that glycine + formaldehyde coupling may be rate-determining in a modern network paper, but no serine-specific abiotic yield conditions were extracted. It is therefore included as a contested network edge rather than a strong demonstrated route (Shemin & Rittenberg, 1950; Okafor et al., 2017; JACS Au 2024 DOI:10.1021/jacsau.4c00685; serine_s6_analysis.md).\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"Green core route via serine nitrile then direct hydrolysis\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal reduced carbon feeds surface glycolaldehyde formation, then the validated Green formamide Strecker chemistry gives serine nitrile, which is hydrolyzed to serine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_005\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P2\",\n      \"name\": \"Green protected reservoir route via N-formylserine nitrile\",\n      \"description\": \"The best-supported quantitative route proceeds from glycolaldehyde to serine nitrile and then to N-formylserine nitrile before alkaline release of serine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_010\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_013\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P3\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanosulfidic direct serine aminonitrile pool to serine\",\n      \"description\": \"Patel-type cyanosulfidic photoredox directly feeds a serine aminonitrile pool, which is then hydrolyzed in aqueous processing.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanosulfidic direct serine aminonitrile pool via protected reservoir\",\n      \"description\": \"The cyanosulfidic network produces serine nitrile, which is stabilized as N-formylserine nitrile in warm formamide and later hydrolyzed to serine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_010\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_013\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal formaldehyde to glycolaldehyde to glycolonitrile to serine nitrile\",\n      \"description\": \"Reduced hydrothermal carbon is converted to formaldehyde, then glycolaldehyde, then glycolonitrile as a precursor node before entering the serine nitrile network.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_005\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal-fed Green route with N-formyl storage and hydrolysis\",\n      \"description\": \"A hydrothermal-to-surface handoff feeds the Green formamide pathway, with N-formylserine nitrile acting as the immediate precursor reservoir before serine release.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_010\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_005\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_013\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n      \"name\": \"Ice photochemistry residue route\",\n      \"description\": \"Cryogenic UV/VUV ice chemistry followed by hydrolysis yields a serine-containing residue from which serine is recovered.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_024\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n      \"name\": \"Spark-discharge direct serine occurrence route\",\n      \"description\": \"Reduced-atmosphere spark discharge produces amino acid mixtures that include serine directly.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_014\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": []\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"name\": \"Spark-discharge glycine plus hydrothermal formaldehyde hydroxymethylation route\",\n      \"description\": \"Spark-discharge glycine is combined with hydrothermal-derived formaldehyde in the retained low-confidence hydroxymethylation concept to give serine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_015\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_022\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanosulfidic glycolaldehyde branch into Green Strecker and protected hydrolysis\",\n      \"description\": \"Cyanosulfidic chemistry supplies glycolaldehyde, which then enters the Green formamide Strecker route to serine nitrile and onward through N-formylserine nitrile to serine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_010\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_013\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_005\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_006\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_005\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_012\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_007\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_011\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_013\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_010\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_002\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_004\", \"rxn_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_006\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}", "parsed_response": {"target_molecule": "Serine", "overall_strategy": "This network follows the literature-supported prebiotic serine system centered on serine nitrile and N-formylserine nitrile as the best-validated intermediate reservoir. The network integrates: (i) hydrothermal generation of C1/C2 feedstocks that can supply surface chemistry; (ii) surface formamide, cyanosulfidic, UV, and evaporative pathways that produce serine nitrile, N-formylserine nitrile, or direct serine-containing mixtures; and (iii) biochemical/prebiotic aqueous reprocessing in which alkaline hydrolysis releases serine from protected aminonitrile intermediates. Because the literature bundle shows that free-serine yield is unresolved while serine-nitrile chemistry is quantitatively supported, the target is reached through multiple convergent precursor routes, with explicit acknowledgment that several terminal conversions are literature-retained but yield-unquantified.", "molecules": [{"id": "mol_001", "formula": "CO2", "iupac_name": "carbon dioxide", "common_name": "carbon dioxide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_002", "formula": "H2", "iupac_name": "molecular hydrogen", "common_name": "hydrogen", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2/h1H", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_003", "formula": "CH2O2", "iupac_name": "methanoic acid", "common_name": "formic acid", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O2/c2-1-3/h1H,(H,2,3)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_004", "formula": "CH2O", "iupac_name": "methanal", "common_name": "formaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O/c1-2/h1H2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_005", "formula": "C2H4O2", "iupac_name": "2-hydroxyethanal", "common_name": "glycolaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H4O2/c3-1-2-4/h1,3H,2H2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_006", "formula": "HCN", "iupac_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "common_name": "HCN", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_007", "formula": "CH3NO", "iupac_name": "methanamide", "common_name": "formamide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH3NO/c2-1-3/h1H,(H2,2,3)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_008", "formula": "NH3", "iupac_name": "azane", "common_name": "ammonia", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_009", "formula": "CH2NOH", "iupac_name": "formamide precursor pool", "common_name": "formamide-forming HCN hydrolysate pool", "inchi": null, "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_010", "formula": "C2H3NO", "iupac_name": "2-hydroxyacetonitrile", "common_name": "glycolonitrile", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H3NO/c3-1-2-4/h2,4H,1H2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_011", "formula": "C3H6O3", "iupac_name": "2,3-dihydroxypropanal", "common_name": "glyceraldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H6O3/c4-1-3(6)2-5/h1,3,5-6H,2H2", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_012", "formula": "C3H6N2O", "iupac_name": "2-amino-3-hydroxypropanenitrile", "common_name": "serine nitrile", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H6N2O/c4-1-3(5)2-6/h3,6H,2,5H2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_013", "formula": "C4H6N2O2", "iupac_name": "N-formyl-2-amino-3-hydroxypropanenitrile", "common_name": "N-formylserine nitrile", "inchi": null, "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_014", "formula": "C4H4N2O2", "iupac_name": "N-formyl-2-aminoprop-2-enenitrile-3-ol dehydration branch", "common_name": "N-formyldehydroalanine nitrile", "inchi": null, "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_015", "formula": "C4H6N2O2", "iupac_name": "beta-formylaminoalanine nitrile derivative", "common_name": "Fo(beta-formylamino)alanine nitrile", "inchi": null, "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_016", "formula": "C3H7NO3", "iupac_name": "2-amino-3-hydroxypropanoic acid", "common_name": "serine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H7NO3/c4-2(3(6)7)1-5/h2,5H,1,4H2,(H,6,7)", "role": "target", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_017", "formula": "H2S", "iupac_name": "sulfane", "common_name": "hydrogen sulfide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2S/h1H2", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_018", "formula": "CH4", "iupac_name": "methane", "common_name": "methane", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH4/h1H4", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_019", "formula": "H2O", "iupac_name": "oxidane", "common_name": "water", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2O/h1H2", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_020", "formula": "CO", "iupac_name": "carbon monoxide", "common_name": "carbon monoxide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CO/c1-2", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_021", "formula": "CH4N2O", "iupac_name": "ammonium chloride/cyanide formamide reaction pool", "common_name": "NH4Cl-NaCN-formamide pool", "inchi": null, "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_022", "formula": "C2H5NO2", "iupac_name": "aminoacetic acid", "common_name": "glycine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H5NO2/c3-1-2(4)5/h1,3H2,(H,4,5)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_023", "formula": "CH3OH", "iupac_name": "methanol", "common_name": "methanol", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH4O/c1-2/h2H,1H3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_024", "formula": "C3H7NO3", "iupac_name": "serine-containing hydrolyzed residue", "common_name": "serine residue pool", "inchi": null, "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}], "reactions": [{"id": "rxn_001", "name": "Hydrothermal CO2 reduction to formate", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_003"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe3S4)", "mackinawite (FeS)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "greigite and mackinawite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "alkaline vent-like, anoxic, H2-rich"}, "mechanism": "Mineral-catalyzed reduction of CO2 by H2 on Fe-S surfaces to a reduced C1 product pool represented by formate.", "reasoning": "Included to satisfy the required hydrothermal-surface interconnection and provide a plausible reduced-carbon feed into later surface chemistry. This hydrothermal step follows the iron-sulfur vent framework specified in the system instructions, but the validated serine literature bundle explicitly notes that hydrothermal/iron-sulfur routes were searched and not promoted into the final retained serine route table, so this connection is speculative and only used as an environmental feeder, not as a literature-backed serine-specific route (Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997; Preiner et al., 2020; serine_s6_analysis.md)."}, {"id": "rxn_002", "name": "Hydrothermal reduction of formate/CO2 pool to formaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_003", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_004"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe3O4)", "elemental iron (Fe0)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "400-500K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "magnetite and Fe0", "aqueous": "true", "other": "anoxic subseafloor or vent-adjacent reducing conditions"}, "mechanism": "Further reduction of a C1 oxocarboxylate/carbon oxide pool to formaldehyde-like reduced carbon under Fischer-Tropsch-type hydrothermal catalysis.", "reasoning": "Used as a hydrothermal source of formaldehyde to connect the required environments; this is not part of the validated final serine route table and therefore is marked as a necessary speculative feeder constrained by the system hydrothermal chemistry. The serine report emphasizes that hydrothermal angles were not retained as final serine routes (serine_s6_analysis.md), while reduced-carbon generation on magnetite/Fe surfaces is broadly supported in prebiotic catalysis literature (McCollom, 2013; Preiner et al., 2020; serine_s6_analysis.md)."}, {"id": "rxn_003", "name": "Surface conversion of HCN hydrolysate pool to formamide", "inputs": ["mol_006", "mol_019"], "outputs": ["mol_009", "mol_007"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO2 and phosphate minerals", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV-exposed evaporative/formamide-rich surface setting"}, "mechanism": "HCN in aqueous irradiated surface settings is converted through hydrolysis/photochemical processing into a formamide-bearing pool, represented here as direct access to formamide.", "reasoning": "Formamide is a principal reagent/solvent in the strongest serine network routes. The validated report identifies formamide as central to SER-R1 to SER-R3 and also retains UV photochemistry from HCN-rich environments. The exact HCN-to-formamide preparative step is not itself route-ranked in the retained table, so this connector is necessary but partly inferred from the validated precursor network and broader HCN/formamide prebiotic chemistry (Green et al., 2023; Patel et al., 2015; serine_precursor_list.csv; serine_s6_analysis.md)."}, {"id": "rxn_004", "name": "Surface formose-type production of glycolaldehyde from formaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_005"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)", "phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "borate minerals and phosphate minerals", "aqueous": "true", "other": "evaporitic pool or hot-spring wet-dry concentration"}, "mechanism": "Surface concentration and carbonyl coupling generate C2 sugar precursors from formaldehyde, represented by glycolaldehyde formation.", "reasoning": "Glycolaldehyde is the direct aldehydic precursor in the best-supported serine nitrile route (SER-R1). The validated report cites glycolaldehyde as a principal feedstock and links it to formose/cyanosulfidic chemistry, but does not give a single retained route row for formaldehyde-to-glycolaldehyde. This connector is therefore necessary to bridge the hydrothermal reduced-carbon supply to the literature-supported surface serine network (Green et al., 2023; Ritson & Sutherland, 2012; Ritson et al., 2013; serine_precursor_list.csv)."}, {"id": "rxn_005", "name": "Cyanosulfidic photoredox generation of glycolaldehyde, glyceraldehyde, glycolonitrile and serine aminonitrile pool", "inputs": ["mol_006", "mol_017", "mol_019"], "outputs": ["mol_005", "mol_010", "mol_011", "mol_012"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)", "TiO2 (anatase/rutile)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "mild / non-hydrothermal", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "UV photoredox with sulfide mineral support", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV-exposed surface waters or post-impact ponds; hydrosulfide-driven cyanometal photoredox"}, "mechanism": "HCN/cyanide and hydrosulfide under UV photoredox furnish sugar and aminonitrile precursor pools including glycolaldehyde, glyceraldehyde, glycolonitrile, and a serine-aminonitrile-containing output.", "reasoning": "This reaction follows SER-R5 as a precursor-supply route. The validated report states that Patel et al. (2015) supports cyanosulfidic generation of glycolaldehyde/glyceraldehyde-class precursors and an alpha-aminonitrile pool including serine aminonitrile, though no serine-specific yield was retained. Because the system requires mineral agents for all surface reactions, sulfide minerals and TiO2 are specified as geochemically relevant supports, while the core chemistry remains the retained cyanosulfidic photoredox network (Patel et al., 2015; serine_reaction_table.csv; serine_s6_analysis.md)."}, {"id": "rxn_006", "name": "HCN addition to glycolaldehyde to form glycolonitrile", "inputs": ["mol_005", "mol_006"], "outputs": ["mol_010"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)", "montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "mineral-assisted concentration in aqueous surface setting", "aqueous": "true", "other": "cyanide-bearing pool, anoxic"}, "mechanism": "Cyanohydrin formation from glycolaldehyde and HCN gives glycolonitrile, a validated precursor linked to serine chemistry.", "reasoning": "The validated precursor list explicitly identifies glycolonitrile as a cyanosulfidic precursor/feedstock linked to glycolaldehyde-class chemistry in serine networks. While no dedicated retained route row quantifies this isolated transformation for serine, it is directly supported as a precursor relation in the literature bundle and helps create the required convergent hub structure (Patel et al., 2015; Green et al., 2023; serine_precursor_list.csv)."}, {"id": "rxn_007", "name": "Green formamide Strecker route from glycolaldehyde to serine nitrile", "inputs": ["mol_005", "mol_006", "mol_008", "mol_007", "mol_021"], "outputs": ["mol_012"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)", "montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "RT 16 h; then 50 C 16 h; then 80 C 16 h", "pressure": "ambient / open vessel", "catalyst": "none additional in paper; mineral concentration support imposed by network constraints", "aqueous": "true", "other": "formamide-rich solution; NaCN 3.0 equiv; NH4Cl 5.0 equiv; evaporative/warm drying microenvironment"}, "mechanism": "Strecker-like aminonitrile formation from glycolaldehyde in formamide-rich medium with cyanide and ammonium gives serine nitrile, with later progression toward N-formylserine nitrile upon continued heating.", "reasoning": "This is the core yield-backed route SER-R1. The validated report gives exact conditions and conversions: glycolaldehyde + NaCN + NH4Cl in formamide under RT to 50 C to 80 C sequence gave up to 36% serine nitrile and then 36% N-formylserine nitrile (Green et al., 2023, JACS, Table 3 row CH2OH; serine_route_yields.csv). Mineral agents are included only to satisfy the output schema constraint; the literature itself reports no added mineral catalyst for this step (Green et al., 2023; serine_s6_analysis.md)."}, {"id": "rxn_008", "name": "Formamide-mediated N-formylation of serine nitrile to N-formylserine nitrile", "inputs": ["mol_012", "mol_007"], "outputs": ["mol_013"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)", "montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "RT to 80 C", "pressure": "ambient / open vessel", "catalyst": "none additional in paper; mineral concentration support imposed by network constraints", "aqueous": "false", "other": "formamide solution; nitrate salt form of serine nitrile used in reported experiments"}, "mechanism": "Formamide acts as reagent/medium to N-formylate serine nitrile, producing a protected aminonitrile reservoir.", "reasoning": "This is SER-R2, the strongest quantitative step in the validated bundle. Green et al. (2023, JACS, Table 1 row 4a) reported conversion of serine nitrile to N-formylserine nitrile reaching 82% at +5 h 80 C. The validated report interprets this as protection/reservoir chemistry rather than direct free-serine synthesis (Green et al., 2023; serine_route_yields.csv; serine_s6_analysis.md). Mineral agents are network-required but not experimentally specified in the paper."}, {"id": "rxn_009", "name": "MgCl2-assisted warm formamide branching of serine nitrile", "inputs": ["mol_012", "mol_007"], "outputs": ["mol_013", "mol_014", "mol_015"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)", "montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "50 C and 80 C", "pressure": "ambient", "catalyst": "MgCl2 5 equiv in formamide; mineral support imposed by network constraints", "aqueous": "false", "other": "drying/warming formamide chemistry; one condition used free-base Ser-CN prepared from pH 9.2 aqueous solution"}, "mechanism": "Under warm formamide conditions with MgCl2, serine nitrile partitions among N-formylserine nitrile and dehydrated/elaborated side branches including FoDHA-CN and Fo(beta-formylamino)alanine nitrile.