ic conditions not extracted; precursor-pool route\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Within the cyanosulfidic network, glycolonitrile and related HCN-derived precursors are transformed through UV/redox chemistry into alpha-aminonitrile pools that include serine nitrile.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"SER-R5 was retained as a non-yield precursor-supply route producing alpha-aminonitrile pools including serine aminonitrile in UV-exposed aqueous hydrosulfide systems. Because the validated report does not provide a fully resolved serine-specific stepwise sequence, this reaction is intentionally broad but still anchored in Patel et al. (2015) and explicitly marked as a precursor-pool route rather than a quantified dedicated serine synthesis (Patel et al., 2015; serine_reaction_table.csv).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_009\",\n      \"name\": \"Formose-like surface supply of glycolaldehyde and glyceraldehyde from formaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_015\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)\", \"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"borate-stabilized sugar-forming conditions\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"evaporitic pool / wet-dry surface setting; included only as a connecting feedstock route because glycolaldehyde and glyceraldehyde are validated serine precursors\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Reduced C1 carbonyl feedstock enters sugar-forming chemistry to furnish glycolaldehyde and glyceraldehyde pools feeding the serine precursor network.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The serine precursor list explicitly identifies glycolaldehyde and glyceraldehyde as upstream serine-relevant feedstocks, but the validated serine route table does not retain a dedicated sugar-forming step. This reaction is therefore a necessary con