e deferring serine-specific chemistry to the retained surface routes (serine_s6_analysis.md)."}, {"id": "rxn_002", "name": "Surface generation of glycolaldehyde and glyceraldehyde precursor pool from cyanosulfidic chemistry", "inputs": ["mol_003", "mol_005", "mol_016", "mol_019"], "outputs": ["mol_004", "mol_014", "mol_015"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["sulfide minerals (molybdenite/stibnite)", "TiO2 (anatase/rutile)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "mild / non-hydrothermal", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "UV-driven cyanometal/sulfidic photoredox with mineral participation", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV-exposed surface waters or post-impact ponds; exact temperature not extracted in validated report"}, "mechanism": "Cyanosulfidic photoredox chemistry produces glycolaldehyde/glyceraldehyde-class carbonyls and glycolonitrile from HCN-derived feedstocks under UV and sulfide-rich surface conditions.", "reasoning": "Retained route SER-R5 identifies cyanosulfidic photoredox as a precursor-supply network generating glycolaldehyde/glyceraldehyde-class precursors and alpha-aminonitrile pools relevant to serine chemistry under UV-exposed aqueous surface settings (Patel et al., 2015). The exact single mineral catalyst was not validated in the report; mineral agents are included here to satisfy the required schema while keeping the reasoning faithful to the reported cyanometal/hydrosulfide photoredox system and noting that this is a precursor-supply rather than serine-specific quantified step (Patel et al., 2015; serine_s6_analysis.md)."}, {"id": "rxn_003", "name": "Formamide-rich Strecker-like formation of serine nitrile from glycolaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_004", "mol_006", "mol_008", "mol_009"], "outputs": ["mol_010"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)", "montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "RT 16 h; then 50 C 16 h; then 80 C 16 h", "pressure": "ambient / open vessel", "catalyst": "none additional in the paper; mineral surfaces here serve concentration and drying support", "aqueous": "false", "other": "formamide-rich solution; NaCN 3.0 equiv; NH4Cl 5.0 equiv; evaporative warm-drying microenvironment"}, "mechanism": "Glycolaldehyde undergoes Strecker-like aminonitrile formation in formamide with cyanide and ammonium chloride to produce serine nitrile.", "reasoning": "This is the strongest validated entry into the serine-specific precursor network: Green et al. (2023) reported up to 36% conversion to serine nitrile from glycolaldehyde with NaCN and NH4Cl under successive RT/50 C/80 C conditions in formamide-rich medium (Table 3 row CH2OH). Mineral agents are not part of the published reaction but are included only as plausible concentrating surfaces required by the framework and not as claimed literature catalysts; the core chemistry and exact thermal sequence follow Green et al. (2023)."}, {"id": "rxn_004", "name": "Formamide-mediated N-formylation of serine nitrile to N-formylserine nitrile", "inputs": ["mol_010", "mol_006"], "outputs": ["mol_011"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)", "montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "RT to 80 C", "pressure": "ambient / open vessel", "catalyst": "none additional", "aqueous": "false", "other": "formamide solution; nitrate salt form of serine nitrile used in reported experiments; warm drying/formamide microenvironment"}, "mechanism": "Serine nitrile is N-formylated/protected by formamide to give N-formylserine nitrile as a stabilized aminonitrile reservoir.", "reasoning": "Green et al. (2023) reported conversion of serine nitrile to N-formylserine nitrile in formamide, reaching 82% at 80 C for 5 h (Table 1 row 4a). The validated report identifies this as the strongest quantitative step in the serine network but stresses that it supports a protected precursor reservoir rather than direct free-serine formation. Mineral agents are added only to satisfy schema constraints and are not asserted as experimentally demonstrated catalysts (Green et al., 2023; serine_s6_analysis.md)."}, {"id": "rxn_005", "name": "MgCl2-assisted warm formamide branching of serine nitrile", "inputs": ["mol_010", "mol_006"], "outputs": ["mol_011", "mol_012", "mol_013"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)", "montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "50 C and 80 C", "pressure": "ambient", "catalyst": "MgCl2 5 equiv", "aqueous": "false", "other": "formamide solution; free-base serine nitrile prepared from pH 9.2 aqueous solution in one condition; branch distributions reported over 20 h at 50 C and subsequent heating at 80 C"}, "mechanism": "Serine nitrile undergoes warm-formamide N-formylation and dehydration/elaboration, partitioning among N-formylserine nitrile, N-formyldehydroalanine nitrile, and Fo(beta-formylamino)alanine nitrile.", "reasoning": "Retained route SER-R3 directly reports this branch network, with MgCl2 5 equiv in formamide producing FoSer-CN, FoDHA-CN, and Fo(beta-formylamino)alanine nitrile under 50 C and 80 C conditions (Green et al., 2023, Table 2 entry 3). This reaction is important because it quantifies attrition from the serine-nitrile hub and shows that the precursor network can both protect and divert material. Mineral agents in the agents field are concentration supports required by schema, whereas MgCl2 is kept in conditions as the literature-specified additive (Green et al., 2023)."}, {"id": "rxn_006", "name": "Alkaline aqueous hydrolysis of N-formylaminonitrile reservoir to serine", "inputs": ["mol_011", "mol_019"], "outputs": ["mol_018"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": ["null"], "conditions": {"temperature": "not fully extracted", "pressure": "ambient", "catalyst": "water / base", "aqueous": "true", "other": "post-drying rehydration; alkaline processing; quantitative free-serine yield unresolved"}, "mechanism": "Rehydration and alkaline hydrolysis of the N-formylaminonitrile reservoir are inferred to release N-formylated and unformylated amino-acid products including serine.", "reasoning": "Retained route SER-R4 is the mechanistically crucial but quantitatively unresolved step linking the formamide aminonitrile network to free serine. The validated report explicitly states that alkaline processing of N-formylaminonitriles is discussed, but no numeric free-serine yield was found in the accessible text or SI. This node is therefore retained as the best literature-grounded release step while clearly marked unresolved (Green et al., 2023; serine_route_yields.csv; serine_s6_analysis.md)."}, {"id": "rxn_007", "name": "Alkaline aqueous hydrolysis of serine nitrile to serine", "inputs": ["mol_010", "mol_019"], "outputs": ["mol_018"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": ["null"], "conditions": {"temperature": "not fully extracted", "pressure": "ambient", "catalyst": "water / base", "aqueous": "true", "other": "post-formamide aqueous processing; included as a necessary connecting hydrolysis edge with unresolved quantitative status"}, "mechanism": "Hydrolytic conversion of the aminonitrile to the corresponding amino acid under aqueous alkaline processing.", "reasoning": "The validated report emphasizes hydrolysis of FoSer-CN and related N-formylaminonitriles, but serine nitrile itself is the immediate amino acid precursor in the same network. This edge is added as a necessary connection to complete the bipartite target network and is explicitly speculative relative to the directly retained route rows, while remaining mechanistically consistent with aminonitrile hydrolysis chemistry discussed around Green et al. (2023). The lack of extracted free-serine yield is acknowledged (Green et al., 2023; serine_s6_analysis.md)."}, {"id": "rxn_008", "name": "Direct cyanosulfidic access to serine nitrile pool", "inputs": ["mol_014", "mol_007", "mol_016", "mol_019"], "outputs": ["mol_010"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["sulfide minerals (molybdenite/stibni