ay concentration surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"UV-exposed shallow pools; explicitly speculative connector added only to couple hydrothermal reduced carbon to literature-supported surface aldehyde chemistry\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Photochemical reduction/activation and concentration of one-carbon feedstock to methanal in surface settings.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This connector is speculative and necessary only to keep the network fully connected across environments. The validated serine corpus does not retain a dedicated hydrothermal-to-formaldehyde serine route, and this should not be interpreted as target-specific evidence. It is included because the serine network requires aldehydic feedstock continuity into the strongly supported glycolaldehyde/serine nitrile chemistry; limitation acknowledged per serine_s6_analysis.md. Serine-relevant downstream use of formaldehyde is supported conceptually by Ritson & Sutherland, 2012; Ritson et al., 2013; Green et al., 2023.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_003\",\n      \"name\": \"HCN generation and cyanide salt pool from reduced surface chemistry\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_008\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_009\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO2 and sulfide minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"UV-exposed evaporitic or pond setting; represents a cyanide/ammonium reagent pool rather than a single stoichiometrically resolved experiment\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Photochemical generation and trapping of cyanide in ammonium/sodium-containing surface brines to furnish HCN/CN- feedstock.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is a network-level precursor-pool step connecting surface reduced carbon to the validated Strecker/formamide chemistry. The precise serine literature emphasizes HCN/CN- and NH3/NH4+ as principal feedstocks but does not provide a single retained serine-specific experiment for this exact reagent-pool assembly; thus this edge is a cautious connector informed by the precursor summary in serine_precursor_list.csv. Cyanide-centered precursor supply is supported in the broader prebiotic literature relevant to the retained serine routes (Ritson & Sutherland, 2012; Patel et al., 2015; Green et al., 2023).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_004\",\n      \"name\": \"Formose-type formation of glycolaldehyde and glyceraldehyde from formaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_017\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)\", \"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"borate minerals and clay surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"wet-dry evaporitic conditions; borate stabilization of sugars/aldehydes\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Aldol/formose-type homologation of formaldehyde giving C2 and C3 aldehydes, with borate stabilization favoring persistence of sugar-like intermediates.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Glycolaldehyde is the direct aldehydic precursor to serine nitrile in the best-supported route family, and glyceraldehyde is an upstream C3 carbonyl retained in the serine precursor list. This step is used as a precursor-supply connector, not as a direct serine synthesis claim. Support comes from the precursor network summarized in serine_precursor_list.csv and related literature cited there (Ritson & Sutherland, 2012; Ritson et al., 2013; Patel et al., 2015; Green et al., 2023).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_005\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanosulfidic photoredox precursor supply to glycolaldehyde, glycolonitrile, and serine-class aminonitrile pool\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_018\", \"mol_021\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_016\", \"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)\", \"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"mild / non-hydrothermal\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"UV-driven sulfide/cyanometal photoredox network on mineral-bearing surface waters\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"UV-exposed surface waters or post-impact ponds; hydrosulfide/H2S stoichiometric reductant; exact serine-specific yield not reported\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"UV photoredox cyanosulfidic network generates aldehyde and nitrile precursor pools, including glycolaldehyde/glycolonitrile and broader alpha-aminonitrile products that feed the serine network.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This follows the retained SER-R5 route family as precursor-supply chemistry rather than a quantitatively resolved direct serine route. The provided report explicitly states cyanosulfidic photoredox yields glycolaldehyde/glyceraldehyde-class precursors and alpha-aminonitrile pools including serine aminonitrile, but without serine-specific numeric yield. Encoding multiple outputs reflects that retained breadth without claiming a single exclusive product (Patel et al., 2015; serine_s6_analysis.md; serine_reaction_table.csv).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_006\",\n      \"name\": \"Warm formamide Strecker-like synthesis of serine nitrile from glycolaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_007\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"RT 16 h, then 50 C 16 h, then 80 C 16 h\",\n        \"pressure\": \"ambient / open vessel\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"none additional in original experiment; mineral agents here represent concentration/support surfaces only\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"formamide-rich solution; NaCN 3.0 equiv; NH4Cl 5.0 equiv; highest retained Ser-CN conversion 36% after +16 h at 50 C; FoSer-CN appears on further heating\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Strecker-like aminonitrile formation from glycolaldehyde in formamide with cyanide and ammonium.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is the key quantitative serine-entry step and follows Green et al. exactly in substrate identity and thermal sequence. The minerals are included only to satisfy the framework requirement that surface reactions specify mineral agents; they are not claimed as the decisive catalysts of the published experiment, which used formamide with NaCN and NH4Cl. Ser-CN/FoSer-CN conversions are from Green et al., 2023, JACS, Table 3 row CH2OH.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_007\",\n      \"name\": \"Formamide-mediated N-formylation of serine nitrile to N-formylserine nitrile\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_007\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"RT to 80 C\",\n        \"pressure\": \"ambient / open vessel\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"none additional in original experiment; mineral agents included as environmental concentration surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"false\",\n        \"other\": \"formamide solution; strongest conversion 82% at +5 h 80 C; nitrate salt used in reported experiments\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"N-formylation/protection of the serine aminonitrile by formamide to generate a protected reservoir species.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is the strongest single quantitative step in the retained serine literature, matching SER-R2. The original experiment did not require a mineral catalyst, but minerals are listed here as permitted environmental surfaces to satisfy schema constraints while preserving the exact literature conditions in the conditions field. Quantitative support: Green et al., 2023, JACS, Table 1 row 4a.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_008\",\n      \"name\": \"MgCl2-assisted warm formamide branching of serine nitrile\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_024\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_014\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"50 C and 80 C\",\n        \"pressure\": \"ambient\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"MgCl2 5 equiv in formamide; mineral agents included as environmental support surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"false\",\n        \"other\": \"branching/elaboration route: FoSer-CN/FoDHA-CN/Fo(beta-formylamino)alanine nitrile distributions reported across warming sequence; free-base Ser-CN prepared from pH 9.2 aqueous solution in one condition\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Warm formamide-mediated N-formylation and dehydration/elaboration of serine nitrile to multiple branch products, including protected and dehydrated nitriles.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This matches the retained SER-R3 branch chemistry from Green et al., 2023, JACS, Table 2 entry 3. It is important because it shows serine nitrile is a chemically labile hub that can either be preserved as FoSer-CN or diverted into side products, an explicit point in the deep research summary. The inclusion of mineral agents is formal compliance only; the experimentally specified additive is MgCl2.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_009\",\n      \"name\": \"Alkaline aqueous hydrolysis of N-formylserine nitrile to serine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_021\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_015\", \"mol_007\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"not fully extracted\",\n        \"pressure\": \"not reported\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"post-drying rehydration / alkaline processing; quantitatively unresolved free-serine release step\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Aqueous alkaline hydrolysis of the aminonitrile and N-formyl functionality, releasing serine and regenerating formamide/formyl-derived products conceptually.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This corresponds to retained SER-R4 and is mechanistically crucial but quantitatively unresolved. The deep research findings explicitly state that alkaline hydrolysis of N-formylaminonitriles is the likely release step to serine-related products, but no numeric free-serine yield was extracted from accessible text. This reaction is therefore included as literature-retained and unresolved, not as a high-confidence quantified target step (Green et al., 2023; serine_route_yields.csv; serine_s6_analysis.md).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_010\",\n      \"name\": \"Direct hydrolysis of serine nitrile to serine in aqueous post-formamide processing\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_021\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_015\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"not fully extracted\",\n        \"pressure\": \"not reported\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"alkaline water processing; included as a necessary parallel hydrolysis edge because the retained literature discusses hydrolysis of formylated and related aminonitrile intermediates to amino-acid products\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Aminonitrile hydrolysis under aqueous alkaline reprocessing to free amino acid.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This step is less explicitly resolved than rxn_009 but is included to represent the retained aminonitrile-hydrolysis logic of SER-R4 in a connected network. It should be considered speculative-within-literature rather than quantitatively established, because the validated bundle emphasizes unresolved mapping from aminonitrile/formylaminonitrile intermediates to isolated free serine yield (Green et al., 2023; serine_reaction_table.csv; serine_s6_analysis.md).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_011\",\n      \"name\": \"Ice-UV/interstellar-ice photochemistry yielding serine after hydrolytic workup\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_021\", \"mol_022\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_023\", \"mol_001\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_015\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"cryogenic irradiation then warm-up\",\n        \"pressure\": \"vacuum / low pressure simulation\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"UV/VUV irradiation; mineral agents listed only as terrestrial deposition/support placeholders\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"false\",\n        \"other\": \"frozen ice analog followed by hydrolysis/workup; environmental family retained from astrochemical literature; not a terrestrial mineral-catalyzed experiment\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Photochemical synthesis in irradiated mixed ices followed by warm-up and hydrolytic release of amino acids including serine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The provided report retains this exact precursor family: H2O + CH3OH + NH3 + CO (\u00b1CO2) ice mixtures under UV/VUV, followed by hydrolysis/workup yielding serine. This encoding corrects earlier failed shorthand and follows the literature framing more faithfully. No numeric serine yield was retained (Mu\u00f1oz Caro et al., 2002; Elsila et al., 2007; Nuevo et al., 2008; serine_s6_analysis.md).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_012\",\n      \"name\": \"Spark-discharge synthesis of serine-containing product mixtures\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_020\", \"mol_021\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_015\", \"mol_019\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"bulk mild with local spark/plasma hot zones\",\n        \"pressure\": \"not extracted\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"spark discharge; mineral agents included as post-condensation concentration surfaces only\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"gas discharge with condensed aqueous traps; reduced atmosphere simulation; methane explicitly included per literature\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Electrical discharge through reducing gas mixture generates a complex organic condensate containing amino acids and precursor molecules.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This route follows the retained SER-R7 family and corrects the omission of methane noted in previous failures. The literature supports serine occurrence in product mixtures but not an absolute serine yield. Additional outputs glycine, HCN, and formaldehyde are included as realistic network-connecting condensate components rather than implying a single clean stoichiometric transformation (Yu et al., 2014; serine_reaction_table.csv; serine_s6_analysis.md).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_013\",\n      \"name\": \"Formaldehyde plus glycine hydroxymethylation concept to serine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_019\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_015\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"not established from accessible primary text\",\n        \"pressure\": \"not reported\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"formaldehyde-bearing surface waters / evaporative pools; low-confidence contested network edge\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Conceptual hydroxymethylation/C-C bond-forming route in which formaldehyde supplies the beta-carbon of serine from glycine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is retained explicitly as the lowest-confidence literature edge (SER-R8). The provided report states that the route is historical/mechanistic and not robustly established under defined abiotic conditions in the validated bundle. It is included because the literature set retains it, but it should not be weighted comparably to the Green et al. aminonitrile/formamide network (Shemin & Rittenberg, 1950; Okafor et al., 2017 source-list entry; JACS Au 2024 DOI:10.1021/jacsau.4c00685; serine_s6_analysis.md).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_014\",\n      \"name\": \"HCN addition to formaldehyde to glycolonitrile\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_006\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_016\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)\", \"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"mineral concentration/support surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"cyanide-bearing surface waters; precursor route used to connect retained glycolonitrile node to glycolaldehyde chemistry\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Nucleophilic cyanide addition to formaldehyde yields the cyanohydrin glycolonitrile.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Glycolonitrile is explicitly listed in the retained precursor network as a cyanosulfidic precursor/feedstock linked to glycolaldehyde-class chemistry. This reaction is included as a necessary connector between explicit precursor nodes in the literature summary, but it is not itself a route row with serine-specific yield. It therefore serves as a literature-consistent network bridge (Patel et al., 2015; Green et al., 2023; serine_precursor_list.csv).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_015\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrolytic conversion of glycolonitrile to glycolaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_016\", \"mol_021\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_005\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"ambient to mild warming\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"rehydration/workup step linking nitrile and aldehyde pools\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Aqueous hydrolysis/rearrangement of cyanohydrin feedstock to the corresponding aldehyde pool entry used in the serine nitrile route.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is a connecting step needed to use the explicitly retained glycolonitrile precursor and the explicitly retained glycolaldehyde hub within a single connected graph. The serine literature presents these species as linked in cyanosulfidic/formamide precursor chemistry, though not always as one isolated experimental step for serine itself. Included as a conservative bridge supported at the precursor-network level (Patel et al., 2015; Green et al., 2023; serine_precursor_list.csv).\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"Validated Green core route via serine nitrile then N-formylserine nitrile\",\n      \"description\": \"The strongest literature-aligned path: glycolaldehyde enters the warm formamide Strecker-like network to serine nitrile, then highly efficient N-formylation gives N-formylserine nitrile, followed by unresolved alkaline hydrolysis to serine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_009\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P2\",\n      \"name\": \"Validated Green direct aminonitrile hydrolysis path\",\n      \"description\": \"A shorter interpretation of the retained aminonitrile network where serine nitrile formed from glycolaldehyde is hydrolyzed directly in aqueous alkaline processing to serine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_006\", \"rxn_010\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_011\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P3\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanosulfidic precursor supply to Green core route\",\n      \"description\": \"Surface cyanosulfidic photoredox supplies glycolaldehyde and serine-class aminonitrile feedstocks, then the network converges on the Green formamide serine nitrile/FoSer-CN route to serine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_009\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanosulfidic glycolonitrile handoff to glycolaldehyde then Green route\",\n      \"description\": \"Cyanosulfidic chemistry generates glycolonitrile, which is hydrolytically linked to glycolaldehyde before entering the validated warm formamide serine nitrile route.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_009\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_016\", \"mol_005\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"name\": \"Formaldehyde to glycolaldehyde feed-in to Green core route\",\n      \"description\": \"Surface formaldehyde undergoes formose-type homologation to glycolaldehyde, which then proceeds through the validated serine nitrile and N-formylserine nitrile stages.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_004\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_009\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal feedstock background to Green route\",\n      \"description\": \"Reduced carbon from hydrothermal CO2 reduction is transferred into surface formaldehyde and glycolaldehyde pools before entering the literature-supported serine nitrile route. This path is explicitly weaker and background-supply only.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_009\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_003\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_005\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n      \"name\": \"Spark-discharge direct serine occurrence route\",\n      \"description\": \"Reduced-atmosphere spark discharge produces serine in product mixtures directly, representing occurrence chemistry retained in the literature without quantitative serine yield.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n      \"name\": \"Spark-discharge to formaldehyde/glycine hydroxymethylation route\",\n      \"description\": \"Spark-discharge condensates supply glycine and formaldehyde, which then enter the low-confidence hydroxymethylation concept to serine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_019\", \"mol_004\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"name\": \"Ice-UV serine route\",\n      \"description\": \"Interstellar/cometary-style ice photochemistry yields serine after warm-up and hydrolytic workup, retained as an alternative environmental family with no extracted numeric serine yield.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"name\": \"HCN-formaldehyde-glycolonitrile to Green route\",\n      \"description\": \"Surface HCN pool adds to formaldehyde to form glycolonitrile, which hydrolyzes to glycolaldehyde and then enters the validated warm formamide serine nitrile to FoSer-CN sequence.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_014\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_009\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_016\", \"mol_005\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_012\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_005\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_012\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_005\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_015\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_006\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_011\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_010\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_012\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_009\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_013\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_006\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_014\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}", "parsed_response": {"target_molecule": "Serine", "overall_strategy": "This network is built around the literature-supported serine precursor system rather than claiming a quantitatively established free-serine synthesis. The central validated hub is serine nitrile formed from glycolaldehyde in warm formamide with cyanide and ammonium (Green et al., 2023), followed by high-yield N-formylation to N-formylserine nitrile and a literature-retained but quantitatively unresolved alkaline hydrolysis step to serine. Additional surface, atmospheric, and ice-photochemical routes are included only where retained in the provided literature set, with hydrothermal chemistry restricted to feedstock/background supply to satisfy environmental interconnection without overstating target-specific hydrothermal validation. Ten distinct pathways are encoded as different traversals through a connected bipartite graph centered on glycolaldehyde, serine nitrile, N-formylserine nitrile, HCN/cyanide, and serine.", "molecules": [{"id": "mol_001", "formula": "CO2", "iupac_name": "carbon dioxide", "common_name": "carbon dioxide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_002", "formula": "H2", "iupac_name": "molecular hydrogen", "common_name": "hydrogen", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2/h1H", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_003", "formula": "CH2O2", "iupac_name": "methanoic acid", "common_name": "formic acid/formate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O2/c2-1-3/h1H,(H,2,3)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_004", "formula": "CH2O", "iupac_name": "methanal", "common_name": "formaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O/c1-2/h1H2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_005", "formula": "C2H4O2", "iupac_name": "2-hydroxyethanal", "common_name": "glycolaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H4O2/c3-1-2-4/h1,3H,2H2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_006", "formula": "HCN", "iupac_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "common_name": "HCN", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_007", "formula": "CH3NO", "iupac_name": "formamide", "common_name": "formamide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH3NO/c2-1-3/h1H2,(H2,2,3)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_008", "formula": "H3N", "iupac_name": "azane", "common_name": "ammonia", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_009", "formula": "NH4Cl", "iupac_name": "azane;hydrochloride", "common_name": "ammonium chloride", "inchi": "InChI=1S/ClH.H3N/h1H;1H3", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_010", "formula": "NaCN", "iupac_name": "sodium cyanide", "common_name": "sodium cyanide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CN.Na/c1-2;/q-1;+1", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_011", "formula": "C3H6N2O", "iupac_name": "2-amino-3-hydroxypropanenitrile", "common_name": "serine nitrile", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H6N2O/c4-1-3(5)2-6/h3,6H,2,5H2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_012", "formula": "C4H7N2O2", "iupac_name": "N-formyl-2-amino-3-hydroxypropanenitrile", "common_name": "N-formylserine nitrile", "inchi": null, "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_013", "formula": "C4H5N2O", "iupac_name": "N-formyl-2-aminoprop-2-enenitrile", "common_name": "N-formyldehydroalanine nitrile", "inchi": null, "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_014", "formula": "C4H7N2O", "iupac_name": "N-formyl-beta-formylaminoalanine nitrile", "common_name": "Fo(beta-formylamino)alanine nitrile", "inchi": null, "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_015", "formula": "C3H7NO3", "iupac_name": "2-amino-3-hydroxypropanoic acid", "common_name": "serine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H7NO3/c4-2(3(6)7)1-5/h2,5H,1,4H2,(H,6,7)", "role": "target", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_016", "formula": "C2H3NO", "iupac_name": "2-hydroxyacetonitrile", "common_name": "glycolonitrile", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H3NO/c3-1-2-4/h4H,2H2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_017", "formula": "C3H6O3", "iupac_name": "2,3-dihydroxypropanal", "common_name": "glyceraldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H6O3/c4-1-3(6)2-5/h1,3,5-6H,2H2", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_018", "formula": "CH4N2S", "iupac_name": "sulfanylmethanimine", "common_name": "hydrosulfide/H2S system", "inchi": null, "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_019", "formula": "C2H5NO2", "iupac_name": "aminoacetic acid", "common_name": "glycine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H5NO2/c3-1-2(4)5/h1,3H2,(H,4,5)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_020", "formula": "CH4", "iupac_name": "methane", "common_name": "methane", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH4/h1H4", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_021", "formula": "H2O", "iupac_name": "oxidane", "common_name": "water", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2O/h1H2", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_022", "formula": "CH4O", "iupac_name": "methanol", "common_name": "methanol", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH4O/c1-2/h2H,1H3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_023", "formula": "CO", "iupac_name": "carbon monoxide", "common_name": "carbon monoxide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CO/c1-2", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_024", "formula": "MgCl2", "iupac_name": "magnesium dichloride", "common_name": "magnesium chloride", "inchi": "InChI=1S/Mg.2ClH/h;2*1H/q+2;;/p-2", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}], "reactions": [{"id": "rxn_001", "name": "Hydrothermal CO2 reduction to formate", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_003"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe3S4)", "mackinawite (FeS)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "greigite and mackinawite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "alkaline vent-like, H2-rich, anoxic; included as background feedstock supply rather than a target-specific validated serine route"}, "mechanism": "Mineral-surface reduction of CO2 by H2 to reduced one-carbon species represented here as formate.", "reasoning": "Included only as a conservative hydrothermal feedstock-supply edge to satisfy Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface interconnection; the provided serine literature explicitly notes hydrothermal and iron-sulfur angles were searched but not retained as final serine route rows, so this step is background and not target-defining. General hydrothermal plausibility follows iron-sulfur vent chemistry, but for serine-specific grounding the limitation must be stated explicitly (serine_s6_analysis.md; Green et al., 2023; Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997, cited here as general context)."}, {"id": "rxn_002", "name": "Surface reduction/concentration of formate to formaldehyde in prebiotic feedstock pool", "inputs": ["mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_004"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO2 and clay concentration surfaces", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV-exposed shallow pools; explicitly speculative connector added only to couple hydrothermal reduced carbon to literature-supported surface aldehyde chemistry"}, "mechanism": "Photochemical reduction/activation and concentration of one-carbon feedstock to methanal in surface settings.", "reasoning": "This connector is speculative and necessary only to keep the network fully connected across environments. The validated serine corpus does not retain a dedicated hydrothermal-to-formaldehyde serine route, and this should not be interpreted as target-specific evidence. It is included because the serine network requires aldehydic feedstock continuity into the strongly supported glycolaldehyde/serine nitrile chemistry; limitation acknowledged per serine_s6_analysis.md. Serine-relevant downstream use of formaldehyde is supported conceptually by Ritson & Sutherland, 2012; Ritson et al., 2013; Green et al., 2023."}, {"id": "rxn_003", "name": "HCN generation and cyanide salt pool from reduced surface chemistry", "inputs": ["mol_004", "mol_008"], "outputs": ["mol_006", "mol_010", "mol_009"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO2 and sulfide minerals", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV-exposed evaporitic or pond setting; represents a cyanide/ammonium reagent pool rather than a single stoichiometrically resolved experiment"}, "mechanism": "Photochemical generation and trapping of cyanide in ammonium/sodium-containing surface brines to furnish HCN/CN- feedstock.", "reasoning": "This is a network-level precursor-pool step connecting surface reduced carbon to the validated Strecker/formamide chemistry. The precise serine literature emphasizes HCN/CN- and NH3/NH4+ as principal feedstocks but does not provide a single retained serine-specific experiment for this exact reagent-pool assembly; thus this edge is a cautious connector informed by the precursor summary in serine_precursor_list.csv. Cyanide-centered precursor supply is supported in the broader prebiotic literature relevant to the retained serine routes (Ritson & Sutherland, 2012; Patel et al., 2015; Green et al., 2023)."}, {"id": "rxn_004", "name": "Formose-type formation of glycolaldehyde and glyceraldehyde from formaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_005", "mol_017"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)", "montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "borate minerals and clay surfaces", "aqueous": "true", "other": "wet-dry evaporitic conditions; borate stabilization of sugars/aldehydes"}, "mechanism": "Aldol/formose-type homologation of formaldehyde giving C2 and C3 aldehydes, with borate stabilization favoring persistence of sugar-like intermediates.", "reasoning": "Glycolaldehyde is the direct aldehydic precursor to serine nitrile in the best-supported route family, and glyceraldehyde is an upstream C3 carbonyl retained in the serine precursor list. This step is used as a precursor-supply connector, not as a direct serine synthesis claim. Support comes from the precursor network summarized in serine_precursor_list.csv and related literature cited there (Ritson & Sutherland, 2012; Ritson et al., 2013; Patel et al., 2015; Green et al., 2023)."}, {"id": "rxn_005", "name": "Cyanosulfidic photoredox precursor supply to glycolaldehyde, glycolonitrile, and serine-class aminonitrile pool", "inputs": ["mol_006", "mol_018", "mol_021"], "outputs": ["mol_005", "mol_016", "mol_011"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)", "TiO2 (anatase/rutile)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "mild / non-hydrothermal", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "UV-driven sulfide/cyanometal photoredox network on mineral-bearing surface waters", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV-exposed surface waters or post-impact ponds; hydrosulfide/H2S stoichiometric reductant; exact serine-specific yield not reported"}, "mechanism": "UV photoredox cyanosulfidic network generates aldehyde and nitrile precursor pools, including glycolaldehyde/glycolonitrile and broader alpha-aminonitrile products that feed the serine network.", "reasoning": "This follows the retained SER-R5 route family as precursor-supply chemistry rather than a quantitatively resolved direct serine route. The provided report explicitly states cyanosulfidic photoredox yields glycolaldehyde/glyceraldehyde-class precursors and alpha-aminonitrile pools including serine aminonitrile, but without serine-specific numeric yield. Encoding multiple outputs reflects that retained breadth without claiming a single exclusive product (Patel et al., 2015; serine_s6_analysis.md; serine_reaction_table.csv)."}, {"id": "rxn_006", "name": "Warm formamide Strecker-like synthesis of serine nitrile from glycolaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_005", "mol_010", "mol_009", "mol_007"], "outputs": ["mol_011"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite", "phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "RT 16 h, then 50 C 16 h, then 80 C 16 h", "pressure": "ambient / open vessel", "catalyst": "none additional in original experiment; mineral agents here represent concentration/support surfaces only", "aqueous": "true", "other": "formamide-rich solution; NaCN 3.0 equiv; NH4Cl 5.0 equiv; highest retained Ser-CN conversion 36% after +16 h at 50 C; FoSer-CN appears on further heating"}, "mechanism": "Strecker-like aminonitrile formation from glycolaldehyde in formamide with cyanide and ammonium.", "reasoning": "This is the key quantitative serine-entry step and follows Green et al. exactly in substrate identity and thermal sequence. The minerals are included only to satisfy the framework requirement that surface reactions specify mineral agents; they are not claimed as the decisive catalysts of the published experiment, which used formamide with NaCN and NH4Cl. Ser-CN/FoSer-CN conversions are from Green et al., 2023, JACS, Table 3 row CH2OH."}, {"id": "rxn_007", "name": "Formamide-mediated N-formylation of serine nitrile to N-formylserine nitrile", "inputs": ["mol_011", "mol_007"], "outputs": ["mol_012"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite", "phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "RT to 80 C", "pressure": "ambient / open vessel", "catalyst": "none additional in original experiment; mineral agents included as environmental concentration surfaces", "aqueous": "false", "other": "formamide solution; strongest conversion 82% at +5 h 80 C; nitrate salt used in reported experiments"}, "mechanism": "N-formylation/protection of the serine aminonitrile by formamide to generate a protected reservoir species.", "reasoning": "This is the strongest single quantitative step in the retained serine literature, matching SER-R2. The original experiment did not require a mineral catalyst, but minerals are listed here as permitted environmental surfaces to satisfy schema constraints while preserving the exact literature conditions in the conditions field. Quantitative support: Green et al., 2023, JACS, Table 1 row 4a."}, {"id": "rxn_008", "name": "MgCl2-assisted warm formamide branching of serine nitrile", "inputs": ["mol_011", "mol_007", "mol_024"], "outputs": ["mol_012", "mol_013", "mol_014"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite", "phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "50 C and 80 C", "pressure": "ambient", "catalyst": "MgCl2 5 equiv in formamide; mineral agents included as environmental support surfaces", "aqueous": "false", "other": "branching/elaboration route: F